Let's first look at the historical data from North Korea. We should look at the historical data to set initial probabilities, but there are a lot of idiosyncrasies about North Korea that are not present with other nuclear states, and their situation is quite unique, so I do not think using "typical nuclear state" data makes sense. We first analyze the probability of detonating a nuclear device. North Korea has detonated 6 devices in the past 15 years that they have had the ability to test a nuclear weapon, leading to a base rate of 6/15 = 0.4. However this has occurred more in recent years as they have gotten more aggressive and admittedly capable in their nuclear powers, in particular in the Obama administration vs the Trump administration. So I think using the base rate of 5 tests in the 8 years of the Obama administration is more accurate, as corroborated in my previous response. This gives a rate of about 60% for detonating a nuclear device every year. There is only half a year until Jan 1 2022, so a chance of 30% for a nuclear test before Jan 1 2022.

However, North Korean authorities plan to slightly reduce the West Sea command’s offensive capabilities relative to the East Sea command, while improving its defensive capabilities. North Korean media reported at the time that the meeting had presented “important tasks to bring about a new turning point in general national defense efforts.” Stressing the need to bolster the defensive capabilities of the Strategic Force, Kim reportedly pointed to the competition between the US and China and the scrapping of US guidelines on South Korean missile development during the recent US-South Korean summit. Kim also apparently said US pressure on North Korea was not simply aimed at denuclearizing the country, but is part of Washington’s international geopolitical strategy toward China. Kim reportedly issued an order that if the United States were to attack China, the West Sea command of the Strategic Force should defend against this and even launch retaliatory strikes. In sum, North Korean authorities believe the US is strengthening its containment of China using the North Korean nuclear issue as an excuse, and that hidden behind the scrapping of the US-South Korean missile guidelines is Washington’s intention to elevate pressure on Beijing.' The move by North Korea authorities to shift the focus of the nuclear issue within the context of Sino-American rivalries, and to stress bolstered military cooperation with China — and even the need for defensive strategies to help Beijing — appears to be aimed at winning Chinese economic cooperation and military support. In fact, Kim repeatedly mentioned the need for strengthening cooperation with China during the latest enlarged meeting of the Central Military Commission and plenary session of the Central Committee. There is also talk in North Korea that Kim could visit China in the latter half of the year. Following the decision to reorganize the Strategic Force, some of the missile systems currently operated by the country’s army, navy, and air force may be transferred to the Strategic Force.'

It is fair to say that North Korea's aggressiveness with respect to their nuclear program will more closely resemble their relations in the Obama administration now than in the Trump administration, considering Trump was focused on appeasement and denuclearization (https://www.cnbc.com/2021/05/21/biden-rejects-trumps-approach-to-north-korea.html) -- Trump took several steps onto North Korean soil, becoming the first American president to do so". This is an approach Biden is sharply rejecting as indicated by this article, with Biden refusing to grant North Korea international recognition. In contrast, while Obama did not take an explicitly aggressive approach, he still refused to grant North Korea legitimacy and held America's position, similarly to Biden: https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/17/world/asia/trump-north-korea-threat.html. With this in mind it is reasonable to assume that relations would pick up through 2021, the first year of the Biden administration, similarly to in 2017; this also seems logical considering Biden and Obama are of closer political background than towards Trump. At the twilight years of the Obama administration in 2016 and 2017, North Korea conducted many nuclear tests and a few ICBM launches, documented at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_nuclear_weapons_tests_of_North_Korea, https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/25/world/asia/north-korea-ballistic-missiles.html, and https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-54500550. So it is reasonable to assume that North Korea will take an aggressive nuclear stance, which is further corroborated by https://www.npr.org/2021/05/02/992874499/north-korea-warns-u-s-over-bidens-big-blunder. However such nuclear tests only occur a few times a year at most in 2016-2017 and ICBM launches are similarly rare, as noted by the previous sources. Such an action would be unwise for North Korea from many perspectives, such as economic, political, etc., as indicated by Biden's aggressive stance. We can see that in 2017 and before North Korea conducted several nuclear tests, and that the ICBM launches then occurred, from the previous sources; it is unlikely that the ICBM launch would occur without the nuclear test according to the historical trend. This logic leads to my answer noted above; the largest single chance is that neither event will occur (say 50% probability), then the next most likely event is that both will if a pattern similar to 2017 plays out (say 30% probability), and then the only remaining larger chance outcome is that North Korea only conducts a nuclear test (say 15% probability).

North Korea does not have many positive international relations so an attack on another country would likely lead to retaliation from multiple countries. If they were to detonate a nuclear device, they would violate the nuclear peace treaty which would have a massive backlash, which makes this highly improbable.

North Korea has been dealing with reduced imports and support from China since the start of the Covid-19 pandemic. At the same time, the North Korean government believes that its missile and nuclear programs are key components of its foreign diplomacy. This means that even if investing in missile/nuclear programs will divert much-needed resources away from civilians, the North Korean government will very likely pursue weapons development to further disrupt US-China relations and potentially initiate sanction-relief talks with the United States. A quick sweep of reported North Korean tests also reveal an interesting pattern - a ramp up of activity in July/August (2017, 2019) and also alternating years between increased and decreased testing. Following these patterns, if North Korea was to detonate a nuclear weapon or launch an ICBM, it would likely to be sometime between July and August. There is not guarantee that the alternating years of activity will continue (especially since these years of inactivity correspond to changes in policy and relations).

Note that a detonation of a nuclear device can happen as a nuclear test, and not necessarily as a direct act of war - likewise with ICBMs. North Korea has conducted nuclear and ICBM tests before - 6 and ~119, respectively, according to Wikipedia. The last nuclear and ICBM tests were in 2017, with the potential range of the missile being 10000+km. Thus the occurrence of another test is not unconceivable in the next year. However, it seems unlikely that tensions with the Biden administration will escalate to this degree within the next 6 months, given the perceived inactivity during the last administration and the world's focus on the current COVID pandemic situation.

North Korea is a PRC vassal state. By extension, they are a middleman for tactical Chinese geopolitical moves, often being a reported source of targeted Cyberattacks. With a new U.S. administration, North Korea (perhaps by extension China), may test the U.S. by launching an ICBM to see how much push back they receive. Periods of heightened N.K. missile testing in the past 15 years are almost always exclusively around and after American presidential election cycles.

North Korea is known to have nuclear and long range ballistic missile capabilities. There is not much reason to detonate a nuclear weapon since we already know they have them, and there may be more severe repercussions for it than just a missile launch. North Korea has a history of launching ICBMs to demonstrate their capabilities, so there may be a launch. However there has not been a very long range missile launch in years.

P(NK detonates nuclear device) = 2.5% because NK may be testing nuclear devices in remote areas to show strength and give itself more bargaining power with the threat of nuclear weaponry. The probability is lowered because the Biden administration & Secretary of State Blinken want to reduce tensions with North Korea (perhaps with pseudo-denuclearization: ‘weak arms control and nonproliferation diplomacy,’ https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-missiles-usa/analysis-biden-faces-calls-to-jumpstart-north-korea-talks-with-more-pragmatic-goals-idUSKCN2AW0EH). I think it is very unlikely that NK will detonate a nuclear device on another country, as that would result in conflict and international condemnation. P(NK nuclear & long range ICBM) = P(NK ICBM | nuclear detonation) * P(nuclear detonation) P(NK long range ICBM | nuclear detonation) = 20%. That is, given that NK will detonate a nuclear device, it will do so via long-range ICBM with a probability of 0.20. In the unlikely event that NK does not simply conduct a nuclear test and attacks another country, the two most likely targets are its neighboring Asian countries or the US. I believe it is more likely to attack its Asian neighbors (and thus, be short range) due to history, politics, and technological considerations. So, P(NK nuclear & long range ICBM) = .2 * .025 = .5% P(NK long range ICBM) = 10% because NK has long-range rockets (>10,000 km) but all such missiles are still “In Development” (https://missilethreat.csis.org/country/dprk/). This probability reflects the fact that NK may increase its development of nuclear weapons technology in light of the growing obsolescence of its military capabilities. NK may want to use such a launch as a scare tactic or as a test. On the other hand, launches are extremely expensive and could draw economic sanctions. P(none) = 1 – P(NK ICBM) – P(nuclear detonation) + P(both) = 1 - .025 - .10 + .005 = 87%

Inside (tech) view: North Korea had two missiles with a (presumptive) 10,000 km range, the Hwasong 14 and 15 - but neither has been tested at that range. It unveiled a new missile in October 2020 that has not been tested, and in January 2021 it unveiled an SLB that has also not be tested. We assume the new missiles have a range equal or greater than the Hwasong 14. As Kogo noted, tests tend to cluster, so it seems plausible that the current cluster will be capped off by the launch of one of the new missiles. His assessment of 30% seems reasonable. Regarding nuclear tests, the rate of 0.6 per year is correct, but in spite of breakdown in negotiations, there is not evidence I could find that North Korea has developed a larger yield nuclear device. NK seems to be focusing more on delivery mechanisms than on larger yields, as the former is more a game-changer in terms of US perception of risk. If NK conducts a test, I predict it will be a test of the miniaturized nuclear warhead that military intelligence believes they possess. However, all tests to date have escalated in size. A test of a smaller device would be technologically useful but symbolically less attractive, unless paired with test of a delivery mechanism. So I judge the likelihood of a nuclear device alone to be lower than the likelihood of both.

North Korea has only conducted 6 nuclear tests since 2006. However, a nuclear device detonation is still more likely given that no missile launched by North Korea has traveled more than 1000km. Though there are reports that the Hwasong-15 can travel 13,000km, it seems more likely that North Korea would use ICBMs with a shorter estimated range - especially with the upcoming Olympics in Japan offering plenty of public attention.
